  "cleanText": "Smallest of all the seeds, almost nothing in your hand, but you bury it one morning and it rises from the land. They say a faith that's small can move a mountain to the sea, so I hold my little handful and I'll see what it can be. Even faith like a mustard seed is faith enough to grow. I believe, help my unbelief, that's the only prayer I know. When the doubt rolls in like weather, I will hold on all the same, cause it's not outside I'm holding, it's the one who holds my name. I have stepped out on the water and I've felt myself go under, but a hand was always reaching through the lightning and the thunder. And the prayers I thought were silent, maybe they were always heard. So I'm leaning on a promise more than feeling more than word. Even faith like a mustard seed is faith enough to grow. I believe, help my unbelief, that's the only prayer I know. When the doubt rolls in like weather, I will hold on all the same, cause it's not outside I'm holding, it's the one who holds my name. There's a man who wrote from prison that he'd learn to be content in the plenty or the empty with whatever life had sent. For the strength was never in him, it was given from above, and the seed don't need to be a tree to rest inside that love. Even faith like a mustard seed is faith enough to grow. I believe, help my unbelief, that's the only prayer I know. When the doubt rolls in like weather, I will hold on all the same, cause it's not outside I'm holding, it's the one who holds my name. So I'll keep a little faith alive, no bigger than a seed, and it's carried me this far, it is all I'll ever need."
